Based on my research, here's a comprehensive guide on **how to set up a custom color palette for mobile-first responsive design in Tailwind CSS (2024/2025)**:

---

## Setting Up Custom Colors in Tailwind CSS

### For Tailwind CSS v3.x (tailwind.config.js approach)

```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
/** @type {import('tailwindcss').Config} */
export default {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      colors: {
        // Single custom color
        'brand': '#FF5A1F',

        // Custom color with shades
        'primary': {
          50: '#f5f3ff',
          100: '#ede9fe',
          200: '#ddd6fe',
          300: '#c4b5fd',
          400: '#a78bfa',
          500: '#8b5cf6',
          600: '#7c3aed',
          700: '#6d28d9',
          800: '#5b21b6',
          900: '#4c1d95',
        },
      },
    },
  },
}
```

### For Tailwind CSS v4.x (CSS-first approach)

Tailwind v4 uses a **CSS-first, token-driven** system with `@theme` blocks:

```css
/* app.css */
@import "tailwindcss";

@theme {
  /* Brand primary color with OKLCH (perceptually uniform) */
  --color-primary-50: oklch(98.3% 0.02 250);
  --color-primary-100: oklch(95.1% 0.03 250);
  --color-primary-500: oklch(68% 0.1 250);
  --color-primary-900: oklch(35% 0.15 250);

  /* Single accent color */
  --color-accent: #FF5A1F;
}
```

---

## Mobile-First Responsive Design

Tailwind CSS is **mobile-first by default**. Breakpoint prefixes apply styles at that breakpoint **and above**:

| Breakpoint | Min Width | CSS |
|------------|-----------|-----|
| `sm:` | 640px | `@media (min-width: 640px)` |
| `md:` | 768px | `@media (min-width: 768px)` |
| `lg:` | 1024px | `@media (min-width: 1024px)` |
| `xl:` | 1280px | `@media (min-width: 1280px)` |
| `2xl:` | 1536px | `@media (min-width: 1536px)` |

### Example: Mobile-First Color Application

```html
<!-- Mobile: primary-500 background, Tablet+: primary-700 -->
<div class="bg-primary-500 md:bg-primary-700 lg:bg-primary-900">
  <p class="text-white p-4">Responsive content</p>
</div>

<!-- Mobile: small text, larger on bigger screens -->
<h1 class="text-primary-600 text-xl md:text-2xl lg:text-4xl">
  Heading
</h1>
```

---

## Dark Mode Theming (v4)

```css
@theme {
  --color-surface: #FFFFFF;
  --color-content: #111827;
}

html.dark @theme {
  --color-surface: #1F2937;
  --color-content: #F9FAFB;
}
```

```html
<html class="dark">
  <body class="bg-surface text-content">...</body>
</html>
```

---

## Usage Examples

```html
<!-- Text colors -->
<p class="text-primary-500">Primary text</p>
<p class="text-accent">Accent text</p>

<!-- Background colors -->
<div class="bg-primary-100">Light primary background</div>

<!-- Hover states -->
<button class="bg-primary-500 hover:bg-primary-600 text-white py-2 px-4 rounded">
  Submit
</button>

<!-- Arbitrary values (one-off colors) -->
<p class="bg-[#32CD32]">Custom green</p>
```

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **v3**: Use `tailwind.config.js` with `theme.extend.colors`
2. **v4**: Use `@theme` blocks in CSS with OKLCH color format
3. **Mobile-first**: Base styles are for mobile; use `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:` for larger screens
4. **Naming**: Use semantic names like `primary`, `surface`, `content` for maintainability
5. **Tools**: Use color generators like [tailkits.com](https://tailkits.com/tools/tailwind-css-color-generator/) or [oklch.com](https://oklch.com) for palette creation

